title: Magnitude 6.5 earthquake hits Mindanao
text:
Philippines Magnitude 6.5 earthquake hits Mindanao (3rd UPDATE) The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) meanwhile registers the quake at 6.7 with an epicenter 14 kilometers north of the southern city of Surigao Published 11:03   11:56   
MANILA, Philippines (3rd UPDATE) – A magnitude 6.5 earthquake struck Mindanao at 10:03 pm on Friday, February 10, according to a report from the US Geological Survey. 
The USGS reported the quake, which struck 10 kilometers north-northeast of Mabua and some 12 kilometers north-northwest of Surigao, as occurring at a depth of 27 kilometers. 
The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center said there was no tsunami threat from the quake. 
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (Phivolcs) said the quake registered at 6.7 with an epicenter 14 kilometers north of the southern city of Surigao. 
Phivolcs has also reported at a number of what appear to be aftershocks following the quake, ranging from 2.7 to 3.9 in magnitude. 
The area's police chief Senior Superintendent Anthony Maghari told radio station DZMM that he saw a school house had collapsed and that many other buildings had developed cracks. 
Many of the residents in the city had fled to higher ground for fear of a possible tsunami, he said. 
Maghari added the city was suffering from a power outage and that police were checking for any casualties. – with reports from the Agence France-Presse/Rappler.com HOW DOES THIS STORY MAKE YOU FEEL? Happy
